heading('Acknowledgements',1)
p('I acknowledge the guidance of my lecturers, supervisors, and peers whose teaching and feedback supported the completion of this eProject. I also acknowledge the tools and resources used in developing the Fanimation interface. This report has been prepared from the delivered React source code and is intended to present the work accurately and professionally.')

heading('1. eProject Synopsis',1)
heading('1.1 Introduction',2); p('Fanimation is a responsive single-page web application that presents a catalogue of fan products and related accessories. It combines a marketing-style landing page with interactive product discovery, product-detail overlays, favourites, a client-side cart, a gallery, offers, frequently asked questions, and a validated contact form.')
heading('1.2 Background',2); p('The implementation models a consumer-facing fan catalogue. Product records are held locally in JavaScript and rendered in React. The interface communicates pricing in Nigerian naira (N) and includes catalogue categories for ceiling, pedestal, wall and exhaust fans, plus accessories.')
heading('1.3 Purpose and Objectives',2)
for x in ['Present a visually organised fan product catalogue.','Allow users to filter and sort the available products.','Allow users to view richer product details, mark favourites, and manage a temporary cart.','Provide supporting promotional, gallery, company, FAQ and contact sections in one scrollable experience.','Demonstrate a responsive React component architecture using Vite, Bootstrap and custom CSS.']: bullet(x)
heading('1.4 Scope',2); p('The delivered application is front-end only. It renders 15 local product records and images. It does not include authentication, a backend API, database, search behaviour, payment execution, checkout processing, order persistence, or message delivery. The visible Checkout button has no click handler; the contact form validates input and shows a local success state only.')
heading('1.5 Technologies Used',2); table(['Technology','Verified use'],[['React 19','Component rendering and local state.'],['Vite 8','Development server and configured production build tool.'],['Bootstrap 5','Grid, form, button, accordion and responsive utility classes.'],['Lucide React','Interface icons.'],['CSS','Component-scoped stylesheet files plus global smooth-scrolling/focus overrides.'],['JavaScript modules','Catalogue data, components and helper functions.']], [1.5,4.7])
heading('1.6 Expected Outcome',2); p('A visitor can browse a responsive Fanimation storefront, narrow its local product catalogue, inspect products in a modal, manage a temporary cart and use the contact-form interaction. These outcomes are implemented as client-side interactions only.')

heading('2. eProject Analysis',1)
heading('2.1 Existing System',2); p('No separate legacy system is present in the uploaded repository. The delivered application itself is the system available for analysis. It behaves as a static, front-end catalogue and promotional site.')
heading('2.2 Problems Addressed',2); p('The interface addresses the practical discovery problem of presenting multiple fan types in a single catalogue. Category, type, colour, brand, price ceiling and sort controls reduce the effort required to browse the 15 available records.')
heading('2.3 Proposed System',2); p('The proposed and implemented system is a React single-page application. It centralises catalogue information in src/data/products.js, composes the page from reusable modules, and keeps transient user interactions in React state.')
heading('2.4 Functional Requirements - Verified',2)
table(['ID','Requirement','Implementation status / evidence'],[['FR-01','Display a promotional homepage','Implemented: Navbar, Ticker, Hero and Features are rendered by App.'],['FR-02','Browse products','Implemented: ProductGrid maps the filtered local catalogue to cards.'],['FR-03','Filter products','Implemented: category, dependent type, price, colour and brand controls.'],['FR-04','Sort products','Implemented: popular (rating), newest (descending id), price ascending and descending.'],['FR-05','View details','Implemented: ProductCard opens ProductModal.'],['FR-06','Manage favourites','Implemented in memory via favourite product IDs and visible count.'],['FR-07','Manage cart','Implemented in memory: add, quantity +/- and subtotal drawer.'],['FR-08','View promotions and gallery','Implemented: oldPrice-derived offers and eight-image lightbox gallery.'],['FR-09','Read FAQs','Implemented: Bootstrap collapse accordion.'],['FR-10','Contact interaction','Implemented: client-side required/email validation and confirmation state.']], [.65,1.8,3.75])
heading('2.5 Non-functional Requirements - Observed',2)
for x in ['Responsive layout through Bootstrap breakpoints and local media queries.','Smooth anchor scrolling with scroll-margin for section targets.','Basic accessibility measures: semantic sections, labels, alt text and aria-labels on important controls.','Fast local data access because the catalogue and assets are bundled with the client.','Maintainability through independently styled component folders.']: bullet(x)
heading('2.6 Assumptions and Constraints',2); p('Catalogue prices are comma-formatted strings and are converted for comparison and calculation. Delivery, warranty, showroom and company statements are presentation content, not integrated business services. LocalStorage stores a browser-local visitor counter; SessionStorage prevents incrementing it more than once in the current browser session. No persistence is provided for favourites or cart data.')
heading('2.7 Feasibility Analysis',2); table(['Area','Assessment'],[['Technical','Feasible for a demonstrator: the client-only architecture has few infrastructure dependencies.'],['Operational','Usable for browsing and enquiry demonstration; not operationally complete for sales because checkout and contact delivery are absent.'],['Economic','Low running complexity for a static deployment; a production service would require API, database, security and payment costs.'],['Schedule','The component/data separation permits focused incremental enhancement.']], [1.3,5.2])

heading('3. eProject Design',1)
heading('3.1 Overall System Architecture',2); p('The browser loads index.html, which mounts main.jsx into #root. main.jsx imports Bootstrap and global CSS, then renders App. App composes the site sections and owns cross-section favourite, cart and cart-drawer state. ProductSection owns the filter state and derives filtered results from allProducts.')
mermaid('Figure 1. Component and data architecture','''flowchart TD\n  Browser --> index[index.html] --> main[src/main.jsx] --> App\n  App --> Navbar & Ticker & Hero & Features & ProductSection & CartDrawer & Gallery & Offers & About & FAQ & Contact & Footer\n  ProductSection --> ProductFilter & ProductGrid\n  ProductGrid --> ProductCard --> ProductModal\n  Products[(products.js: local array)] --> ProductSection\n  Products --> Gallery\n  Products --> Offers\n  AppState[(favourites/cart state)] --> Navbar\n  AppState --> ProductSection\n  AppState --> CartDrawer''')
heading('3.2 Folder Structure',2); code('''src/\n  assets/images/                 hero, logo and 15 product photos\n  components/                    14 feature/component folders\n    ProductSection/ProductGrid/ProductCard\n  data/products.js               catalogue, allProducts and toNumber\n  styles/global.css              global scroll/focus styling\n  App.jsx                        application composition and shared state\n  main.jsx                       React bootstrap and Bootstrap imports\npublic/                          favicon.svg and icons.svg\npackage.json                     scripts and dependencies\nvite.config.js                   React plugin configuration''')
heading('3.3 Navigation and Application Flow',2); p('Navbar and footer links use in-page anchors. Product-category links dispatch a CustomEvent named fanimation:filter-category; ProductSection listens for it, updates category filter state and the page scrolls to the products section. The Hero button scrolls to products directly. On mobile, Navbar displays an overlay panel controlled by isMenuOpen.')
heading('3.4 State Management',2); table(['State owner','State','Purpose'],[['App','favoriteIds','Array of product IDs; toggled by cards/modal and shown in Navbar.'],['App','cartItems, isCartOpen','Cart records/quantities and drawer visibility.'],['ProductSection','filters','Category, type, price ceiling, colour, brand and sort selection.'],['ProductCard','showModal','Whether its detail modal is rendered.'],['Gallery','activeImage','Selected lightbox image.'],['Contact','form, errors, submitted','Controlled form, validation feedback and local success message.'],['Navbar','visitorCount, isMenuOpen','Browser-local counter and mobile menu visibility.'],['Ticker','now','Live one-second clock.']], [1.4,1.5,3.6])
heading('3.5 Data Flow and Filtering',2); p('allProducts is the authoritative current catalogue. ProductSection derives the maximum price and option lists with useMemo. It filters by exact category/type/colour/brand match and numeric price ceiling. It then sorts a copied result set. Changing category clears a previously selected type because that type may no longer be valid.')
heading('3.6 Styling and Responsive Design',2); p('Bootstrap supplies the container/row/column grid and responsive breakpoints. Each module imports its own CSS file. Gallery changes from four columns to three below 992px and two below 576px. Navbar switches to a mobile overlay at 991px and below. About stats stack at 576px. Modal padding/image size reduce at 576px. Product columns use col-lg-4 col-md-6, producing three columns on large screens and two on medium screens before stacking on small screens.')

